description.text:
I created this as I have studied Fine Art and its now become a hobby for me, when using colored pencils I can never find the right shade straight away, I’d always have to pick a few of a color and decide what works best for a brunch of mixed up pencils, the design of the pencil holder is unique as each pencil is held at an angle so you can see a rainbow effect allowing me to pick the color of choice easily. This also makes its much more pleasing to look at and stores the pencils away safely.

Many designs of pencil holders hold all pencil into one section making it difficult to get to certain colors and items like sharpeners and rubbers, so i decided to make one that was still big enough to accommodate a large number of pencils and be easy to select while holding other items in the center for easy of access

title: Screwless towel hook for bathroom cabinet mirror (DEATH TO THE STUPID SUCTION CUP HOOK)

description.text:
So we use a suction cup hook in the bathroom instead of drilling yet more holes into the wall. I read I should use hairspray so it sticks better. I have to pic it up every two weeks or so.
And it makes a ugly spot onto the tiles.
Why didn't I think of using my 3D printer earlier to finally fix this issue?

One of the images is the side view of our Ikea bath mirror cabinet. It rests against a ceramic tile backsplash.
The wood frame of the cabinet is ~1.2mm thick, and so there's a gap to the backplane wood.
So my idea was to print a hook that just clamps in between cabinet and wall, with a small border that rests on the cabinet's backside border. TADA! I also added text, but the files are without text so you can put your own in. You may have to change the thickness depending on your printer, the gap behind your cabinet, and the thickness of the border. No need to drill into the tiles anymore.

!!!! RED ALERT !!!!
If your cabinet does not rest snug against the wall or does not have a border at the back, you can not use this thing. !!!! FIRE !!!!
Print it on it's side to have a continous layer, but print it laying to avoid support (depending on the hook shape!) If you print it laying, the hook will be made of lots of slices and breaks easier... PP3DP UP owners: The thin section - when printed on the side - will be printed as two walls with a gap :( Make it smaller so they touch or thicker so it consists of more layers, but watch out that it still fits and does not get to fragile.

description.text:
This Halloween pumpkin version of my water bottle tote that attaches to your belt loop. It prints in two parts, attached using acetone (nail polish remover). Add a ring from a key ring and a simple carabiner clip.

For the one shown, I started printing in orange and then paused once it had completed the flat portion, changed to black filament and resumed the print.

NOTE: Not all water bottles are created equally. I found that the bottles from Costco (Kirkland brand) are slightly larger at the base and do not slide in easily. The inner diameter is 67mm (~2.64 inches). You may want to scale the stl file up a percent or two to make it more universal.

Printer:

FlashForge Creator Pro

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.2

Infill:

50% or higher for strength

Notes:

The base requires no supports. The top portion needs a support or two for the arch where the ring attaches. It can be printed at 15-20% infill but I prefer to go up to at least 50% for added strength. The lower the infill, the more fragile the long shaft will be. .

Print the two parts. Wipe the inside opening on the top portion with acetone, and wipe (or dip ) the top of the rod for the lower portion in acetone and press together. Wipe additional acetone on top of and below the two pieces and hold until set. Run ring through the hoop and connect the carabiner clip. Attach top belt and walk around town with hands free water bottles

This is a spool holder i designed to hold third party 1kg spools. When you first load these spools (SEE PICTURE) the filament is wound right up to the edge of the spool. The filament can easily come off the spool edge and tangle itself on the spindle.

The angular attachment I designed overcomes this issue.

3D Printing - Print the thread of the object first. The Up Plus 2 or Up Box are best suited to print these objects and provide excellent and easily removable print support on the threads.

I have also included a straight spool base to accommodate other large spools that would not fit on the angular base.

comments.text: Wonderful post.  After having printed a couple of spool holders that attach to the inbuilt one and not having them work as well as I'd hoped, I was considering creating an angled one but never got around to it.  Very glad that someone else beat me to it!  Awesome work!

description.text:
The idea was to create a game for my kitten. So initially I wanted to do a kind of mouse able to walk even if it had been turned upside down.
As always, if possible, I try to make everything from recycled materials. Then, using the principle of operation of the "BristleBot" (many examples in youtube), I created this species of mouse (although actually reminds me more of a hedgehog ..).
Unfortunately I have to confess that the cat does not seem very interested .. I am convinced that he would have preferred if it had been made Âwith edible material ...
Here's a video: http://youtu.be/PRgVewKrWZA

Materials needed:
  • A microswitch 6.2 x 6.2 x 4.1mm (very common, I recovered from an old printer).
  • A engine vibration for smartphones: diameter, 6mm x 19mm maximum length (including acentric)
  • A paper clip (0.8mm diameter)
  • Two battery (type 1.5v LR754)
  • Nylon fishing thread
  • Double-sided tape
  • A piece of doormat
    • instructions:
  • Insert the motor and putting out the wires into the slot
  • fold piece of paper clips, and solder it to the microswitch
  • Solder a wire of the engine to microswitch
  • Insert the microswitch
  • Insert and tied into the small holes of the nose and tail a few pieces of nylon thread
  • Tighten the two threaded parts in the nose and tail to the right depth, and if you need use glue to lock.
  • Cut to fit three pieces of doormat and secure them with double-sided adhesive
    • good job

description.text:
Components for the game "Terraforming Mars" by Stronghold games;

-"Player Cards" which sit atop (or in place of) the player card you use and play on for the game

-"Cube Trays" that help hold together the different unit cubes (gold, silver, bronze)

-"Hex" and "Card holders" that will house your cards and hex tiles for storage as well as play

Plus some other misc pieces. The card holders should all be sized for sleeves, I personally have mine sleeved with 64.5x90mm sleeves and they fit perfectly snug.

Hellas & Elysium, Venus Next, and Prelude compatible!!

The "TM - Hex and Cardsv4.0" (comes in two parts) will hold all cards for the game with room to spare! They sit atop the Venus Next and Hellas & Elysium boards in your box. Unfortunately I am having trouble figuring out how to fit the "... Player card 2.x" versions of the player card into the box with the new card holders. Currently only the "... Player card 1.x" seem to fit nicely in between.

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2 or .3 - Don't bother with anything below .2

Infill:

20% or higher.

What exactly do I need to print to fit my box and game?

5 "Player cards"

I would recommend (though feel free to pick and choose) printing 5 copies of the "TM - Player Card Split 1.2" you'll notice they are in two pieces to help fit on some smaller beds.

Please note, depending on what player cards you choose you may not be able to fit everything in the box. Heed my recommendation for the TM - Player Card Split 1.2 version and see the pictures I posted in the album of my box.

1 Card and Hex Tile holder

The newest one I posted should have plenty of room for sleeved and "naked" cards (including fitting in all Venus Next and Prelude cards). If you do make my newest one I strongly recommend welding the pieces together with acetone, and for that matter paint a little acetone over the whole piece, it should make it a bit stronger and tougher.

1 or 2 Cube Trays

My favorite one which seems to work the best so far is the "Terraforming Mars - Cube Tray split - Small - scalloped"

description.text: The Kinect was designed to sit in front of a TV, not carried around in your hand. Since I've started playing with Kinect Fusion style 3D scanning, ie: http://reconstructme.net - I found it awkward to carry it around and point it at things. So I decided it needed a handle. Since this creates a standard tripod mount screw on the top of the pistol grip, it can be used to attach to anything that is made to connect to tripods. So it should work with most cameras and other Kinect tripod adapters. Also, if you happen to have a real AR-15 grip, you could probably use that too. Make Art, Not War!

Besides the printed parts, you'll need: 2 x 1/4"-20 nuts
4 x M2.6x8 cap screws (or better yet #4 - 1/2" Phillips Pan Head Boss Screw)
2 x 1/4"-20 screws 0.75" long Because of overhang, I added a 1 layer thick wall in the main shaft above the trapped nut on the adapter. Just push through it with the end of a screwdriver. Also, the internal screw hole on the adapter is slightly undersized so that you can tighten it by digging teeth into the plastic when you screw it in to attach it to the pistol grip.

description.text:
This project was inspired by Project: Rubberband Glider (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1744950). While its not a direct remix of the original files. Everything here was made by me and my daughter (Grade 3). I thought it important to give proper attribution. As the idea behind this idea was mostly inspired by insane66's version.

This is my first thing upload, so let me know if I'm doing it wrong :D
Its also the first time I have designed an aircraft more complex that a paper plane, so there are bound to be mistakes. Let me know what I did wrong so it can be improved in future models.

This thing is a work in progress. More photos, video and thing files will be uploaded as they are made.

The idea here is to make your own modifications, or your own new version and share it for others to try or to be inspired. See what you can come up with! Show us how it flies. Tell us why you did what you did and if it performed to expectation. If it fails, try to find out why and share with the community so others can avoid that mistake, or fix it, or repeat it and learn from the mistake.

There is video about how I came to make this thing and some clips of it gliding on youtube
https://youtu.be/BfO1I9xDWLM

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

i3 Prusa

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2-0.4

Infill:

5-10%

Notes:

This thing is supposed to glide as far as possible. So like all aircraft it should be light weight.
Use as little material as possible while still being strong enough to survive a few hard landings. I printed in ABS to get the best strength and flexibility to weight ratio. I would love to see how it goes in other materials.

The first V1 body was printed in 0.2 layers with 1 perimeter, 1 top and bottom layer and 5% infill. This was not quite strong enough, although it did survive an hour or mores play with lots of crashing.

The V1 aerofoil wings should be printed vertically.

The V1 aerofoil wings are very thin and may suffer from weak layer bonding. I found painting the ABS with acetone made them a lot stronger.
My V2 aerofoils did not print well and need some sanding and patching with ABS sheet.
I will add video of that process once its been completed.

Some of these wing designs are challenging prints. If they go bad use your imagination and experiment with different methods of repair or modification.

What we learned and discovered. While making this thing with my child we discussed many aspects of physics and mathematics.
As an almost 9y/o grade 3 student she found the measuring involved in making a design with no degrees of freedom very educational. Expanding on stuff she was doing at school while making something she could use that has a function. While still being more fun than a traditional measuring exercise at school. We also looked at aerodynamics, with the wing angles, aerofoils, body design, weight distribution and tail rudder. Discussing the roles of each part of the glider and what it needed to do.
We looked at structural integrity vs low weight when choosing print settings for infill and outer layers etc. As well as examining broken bits to see why they failed. As a grown adult with years of building, design and modification experience. I also found there is a lot I could learn about many of the above points and more.
There is something to be learned here for anyone, from a grade 3 level student to a university level engineer. I would be surprised if anyone could try this and not learn something new. Most importantly. We both had a heap of fun doing this project.

The main goal for my twist on this project was to have a lot of fun with my child. The learning comes easy while doing something fun that also makes you think. Explorament!
I would recommend allowing children/students as much freedom in their design process as possible.
Allow lots of time for flying, crashing and examining failures, as well as successful aspects of various designs.
I am not a teacher. If you are plan this lesson as you see fit. Let me know what you covered. Be sure to check out the original project as it has some fairly comprehensive lesson guides.

This version was made mostly with ABS. Try not to be too limiting here.
Project glider can be made with a huge variety of materials and should not be restricted to 3D printing.

• CAD
  • measuring
  • structural design
  • engineering
  • aeronautical
  • print settings
  • having fun
  • throwing

What else can you make this from?

While I did this project to test my 3D printer and challenge my skills using it. You do not have to make this with a 3D printer. It could be made from cardboard, Styrofoam, Balsa wood, or any light weight craft materials.

Be creative. How else can you make a project glider. Share it online so others can be inspired and have fun while learning.

It should be possible to adjust the values to produce a new printable model that will fit sufficiently tightly around other pillowed-rectangle shaped lenses. Maybe an old pair of prescription lenses could be used. My primary reason for uploading is that someone else may find the measurements for the outer frame in the freecad model useful.

If you do try to use this design however, I suggest adjusting the values in the "LH" and "LENS" spreadsheets. The "UC" spreadsheet controls the outer shape and shouldn't need to be adjusted. Then cut out everything but one of the central 'holder' parts, and print that out until it fits.

Warning: this puts the lenses very close to the rift's own Fresnel lenses (at least for my prescription), so be careful!

This is a UK plug adapter to fit over existing ones. A few of my plugs have plastic ground pins because by law they have to for safety however I have dropped some of them and broke them off rendering them useless. I have tried to glue them on but they do not have enough surface area to have the glue hold so it breaks off again. This is to fix it.

comments.text: Nice idea - but potentially dangerous. It is similar to the socket blanks intended to keep children from meddling with a socket outlet (these are stupid too, see http://www.fatallyflawed.org.uk/) - except this one would leave the shutters on a socket open for a metalic object to then be inserted. Clean after print

Clean the filament hole with a piece of filament and some toothpaste or something like this (little abrasive). Rinse. It also works with a piece of filament with toothprints of the feeder (you get after changing the filament). Or use a needle file to smooth the hole.

Disassemble

!!! you will loose your flux warranty now !!!
open the top housing of flux. remove the feeder motor and mechanics. (2 screws)
watch for the spring!!

remove the springarm with the roller on the rotation axis. (little spring ring)

remove the motor from the support. (4 screws)

remove the lower filament guide (brass piece)

remove the quick tube adapter from the brass piece. You dont need the brass piece for the new version.

Assembling

Screw the printed adapter, motor support and motor together (same 4 screws)
Check that the motor turns free inside the printed piece.

Screw quick adapter with slight pressure through the opening of the motor holder (where previously the brass piece was) into the printed part. The thread cuts itself.

Apply the spring arm with roller.

Now you can remount the feeder in flux.
